<subSubSection id="B291B68B9E5CFF8C6DBAFED9305FC66F" pageId="11" pageNumber="442" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="FA34E5009E5CFF8C6DBAFED9305FC66F" blockId="11.[151,1436,151,321]" pageId="11" pageNumber="442">
<emphasis id="C8FF39129E5CFF8C6DBAFED93272C633" bold="true" box="[199,328,259,285]" pageId="11" pageNumber="442">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name derives from the fact that the male genitalia of the 
<typeStatus id="25305BA29E5CFF8C697FFED9375EC633" box="[1026,1124,259,285]" pageId="11" pageNumber="442">holotype</typeStatus>
is devoid of a protuberance of the sacculus on one side, which was absent before dissection.
</paragraph>
